# TypeScript Architecture & Refactoring Excellence

## Core Architecture Principles
- **Modular Design**: One module/domain, single responsibility, clear boundaries
- **SOLID Compliance**: Single responsibility, open/closed, Liskov substitution, interface segregation, dependency inversion
- **Composition over Inheritance**: Prefer composition for flexibility and testability
- **Layer Separation**: Distinct layers for presentation, business logic, data access

## TypeScript Excellence
- **Strict Typing**: No `any`, explicit types for all variables/functions/parameters/returns
- **Interface Contracts**: Define clear interfaces for component/service contracts
- **Immutability First**: `readonly` for unchanging data, `as const` for literals, functional updates
- **Advanced Types**: Union types, discriminated unions, mapped types, conditional types

## Code Quality Standards
- **Function Constraints**: <20 executable lines, ≤4 parameters, single purpose, verb-first naming
- **Class Limits**: <200 lines, <10 public methods, <10 properties, single responsibility
- **Naming Conventions**: PascalCase (classes), camelCase (variables/methods), kebab-case (files), UPPERCASE (constants)
- **File Organization**: One export per file, logical imports grouping, barrel exports for clean APIs

## Refactoring Priorities
- **Performance**: Memoization, lazy loading, efficient algorithms
- **Maintainability**: DRY principle, clear abstractions, comprehensive documentation
- **Readability**: Self-documenting code, meaningful names, consistent formatting
- **Testability**: Dependency injection, pure functions, clear side-effect boundaries

## Component Architecture Patterns
- **Functional Components**: Use with explicit prop interfaces for type safety
- **Custom Logic Abstraction**: Hooks/utilities for reusable logic, state machines for complex state
- **Component Separation**: Smart/presentational component distinction for clear responsibilities
- **Composition over Nesting**: Prefer component composition for flexible architectures

## Service Layer Patterns
- **Business Logic Encapsulation**: Dedicated service layers for domain logic separation
- **Dependency Injection**: Constructor injection for testability and loose coupling
- **Module-per-Domain**: Clear boundaries with single responsibility per module
- **Cross-Cutting Concerns**: Shared modules/utilities for common functionality

## Data Flow & State Management
- **Reactive Patterns**: Observable/event-driven data flow for responsive applications
- **State Machine Architecture**: Complex state management through structured state machines
- **Immutable Updates**: Functional state updates to prevent side effects
- **Clear Boundaries**: Well-defined interfaces between data access and business logic

## Error Handling & Resilience
- Exceptions for unexpected errors, validation for expected cases
- Global error boundaries with context preservation
- Graceful degradation, user-friendly error messages
- Comprehensive logging with structured data

## Testing Strategy
- Unit tests for pure functions, integration tests for modules
- Arrange-Act-Assert pattern, meaningful test names
- Test doubles for dependencies, acceptance tests for critical paths
- Coverage metrics with quality over quantity focus

## Performance Optimization
- Bundle splitting, tree shaking, code splitting
- Efficient algorithms, memoization, virtualization
- Lazy loading, prefetching, caching strategies
- Runtime performance monitoring and profiling

## Documentation & Communication
- JSDoc for public APIs, inline comments for complex logic
- Architecture decision records for significant changes
- Code review guidelines, consistent commit messages
- Living documentation updated with code changes